  "prompt": "Is the elephant-headed god \"Ganesh\" or \"Ganesha\"?",
  "response": "The elephant-headed deity from Hinduism is most accurately spelled **\"Ganesha\"**. This spelling is a direct transliteration from the Sanskrit name \u0917\u0923\u0947\u0936 (Ga\u1e47e\u015ba), where:\n\n- **\"Ga\u1e47a\"** means \"multitude\" or \"groups\" (often interpreted as the leader of the ganas, the attendants of the god Shiva).\n- **\"I\u015ba\"** means \"lord\" or \"master.\"\n\nWhile **\"Ganesh\"** is also commonly used, especially in English-speaking contexts, \"Ganesha\" is generally preferred for its closer adherence to the original Sanskrit pronunciation and spelling.\n\n### Additional Information:\n\n- **Role and Significance:** Ganesha is widely revered as the remover of obstacles, the patron of arts and sciences, and the deva of intellect and wisdom. He is often invoked at the beginning of new ventures and ceremonies.\n\n- **Iconography:** Typically depicted with an elephant head on a human body, Ganesha has various attributes, including a broken tusk and a pot-belly, each symbolizing different aspects of his character and mythology.\n\nBoth \"Ganesh\" and \"Ganesha\" are understood and accepted, but if you're aiming for accuracy, especially in academic or formal contexts, \"Ganesha\" is the recommended spelling.",
